\section{Methodology}

In this section, we present the Multi-scale Angular Cost Volume Network (MACVO-Net), a unified framework designed for robust depth estimation in non-Lambertian light fields. Conventional learning-based approaches predominantly rely on implicit feature extraction from sparse angular subsets, which fundamentally limits their performance when confronted with complex specular or transparent materials \cite{heber2018, wang2023}. MACVO-Net circumvents the strict viewpoint consistency assumption by explicitly utilizing all 81 available angular views to construct a 4D cost volume. In non-Lambertian regions, any discrete disparity hypothesis yields a high photometric matching cost, causing the resulting cost volume to naturally flatten. The network interprets this geometric flatness as an inherent physical uncertainty signal, effectively isolating unreliable measurements without requiring hand-crafted occlusion or material masks.

The network input consists of a structured light field captured by a plenoptic camera, comprising an array of $9 \times 9 = 81$ views. During preprocessing, the raw optical data is normalized and spatially downsampled or cropped to a target spatial resolution of $H \times W$, specifically $128 \times 128$ pixels, yielding an input tensor $\mathbf{I} \in \mathbb{R}^{B \times 81 \times C_{in} \times H \times W}$, where $B$ denotes the batch size and $C_{in}$ represents the input color channels. We explicitly decouple this input into a center view $\mathbf{I}_{center}$ and 80 non-center views $\mathbf{I}_{i}$. The center view anchors the spatial geometry and serves as the primary reference, while the surrounding 80 views provide the dense angular distribution required to characterize complex reflectance properties. 

As illustrated in Fig.~\ref{fig:architecture}, the overall data flow decouples spatial texture extraction from explicit angular matching. The center view is first processed by the FeatureEncoder, which employs successive convolutional layers with internal skip connections to project the raw pixel intensities into a compact 32-channel feature space. This mapping preserves high-frequency spatial textures while providing a stable basis for subsequent matching:
\begin{equation}
\mathbf{F}_{center} = \text{Encoder}(\mathbf{I}_{center}) \in \mathbb{R}^{B \times 32 \times H \times W}.
\end{equation}
Simultaneously, the CostVolumeBuilder evaluates spatial correspondences across the entire angular domain. For each disparity hypothesis $d$ selected from a predefined range of 32 discrete values, the 80 non-center views are warped to align with the center view according to the disparity shift. The absolute photometric differences between the warped views and the center view are averaged to compute the matching cost:
\begin{equation}
\mathbf{C}(d) = \frac{1}{80} \sum_{i=1}^{80} \|\text{Warp}(\mathbf{I}_{i}, d) - \mathbf{I}_{center}\|_1.
\end{equation}
This explicit aggregation across 80 views forms the 4D cost volume $\mathbf{C} \in \mathbb{R}^{B \times 32 \times H \times W}$. We concatenate the 32-channel center view features $\mathbf{F}_{center}$ and the 32-channel cost volume $\mathbf{C}$ along the channel dimension, producing a unified 64-channel joint representation. 

This joint representation is fed into a multi-scale U-Net architecture to synthesize the final depth map \cite{ronneberger2015}. The U-Net Encoder performs three sequential stages of spatial downsampling, progressively expanding the receptive field and extracting hierarchical spatial-semantic features. The channel dimension expands systematically through the downsampling blocks, following a $64 \rightarrow 128 \rightarrow 256$ progression, yielding a deep feature map of shape $\mathbb{R}^{B \times 256 \times H/8 \times W/8}$. The U-Net Decoder subsequently reconstructs the spatial resolution through a symmetric sequence of upsampling stages. At each resolution scale, features propagated from the decoder are concatenated with the identically scaled features bypassed from the encoder via skip connections \cite{lin2017}. This multi-scale fusion path allows the network to combine coarse semantic depth cues with fine spatial boundaries, while dynamically suppressing depth hypotheses originating from the flattened, high-uncertainty non-Lambertian cost volume regions.

A final $1 \times 1$ convolutional layer transforms the decoded features into the output space. The network outputs a single-channel continuous depth map $\mathbf{D} \in \mathbb{R}^{B \times 1 \times H \times W}$. By processing the joint representation through the deep U-Net architecture, the framework generates dense, sub-pixel accurate disparity maps that remain robust against the texture-copying and depth-blurring artifacts typical in non-Lambertian scenarios \cite{eigen2014}.

\subsection{FeatureEncoder (中心视角特征提取)}

The FeatureEncoder module isolates the central view from the angular domain to establish a robust spatial prior. Conventional learning-based light field depth estimation architectures predominantly feed stacked angular patches directly into convolutional neural networks, forcing the network to simultaneously disentangle angular consistency and spatial features \cite{heber2018}. This implicit coupling degrades performance in non-Lambertian regions, where high-frequency specular reflections generate misleading photometric gradients that destabilize feature extraction. By explicitly extracting features from the center view, $\mathbf{I}_{center}$, which serves as the reference coordinate for the entire plenoptic function, we decouple the spatial context from the angular matching process. This extracted feature provides a stable structural anchor, mitigating the influence of non-Lambertian artifacts before angular aggregation.

The architecture adopts a residual learning paradigm to preserve high-frequency textural details while mapping the input into a high-dimensional latent space. Given the central view $\mathbf{I}_{center} \in \mathbb{R}^{B \times C_{in} \times H \times W}$ extracted from the full light field, where $C_{in}$ represents the input color channels, an initial $3 \times 3$ convolutional layer projects the image into a $32$-channel feature space. This initial projection is processed through a sequence of $L$ residual blocks. For the $l$-th residual block, the forward propagation is formulated as:
\begin{equation}
\mathbf{F}^{(l)} = \text{ReLU}\left( \mathcal{W}_2^{(l)} * \text{ReLU}\left( \text{BN}\left( \mathcal{W}_1^{(l)} * \mathbf{F}^{(l-1)} \right) \right) \right) + \mathbf{F}^{(l-1)}
\end{equation}
where $\mathbf{F}^{(l-1)}$ and $\mathbf{F}^{(l)}$ denote the input and output feature maps of the $l$-th block respectively, with $\mathbf{F}^{(0)}$ being the initial projection. The operators $\mathcal{W}_1^{(l)}$ and $\mathcal{W}_2^{(l)}$ represent the learned weights of the two $3 \times 3$ convolutional layers within the block. The symbol $*$ denotes the convolution operation, BN denotes Batch Normalization, and $\text{ReLU}(\cdot)$ is the Rectified Linear Unit activation function. The skip connection, represented by the addition of $\mathbf{F}^{(l-1)}$, ensures that the base spatial gradients and edge information from the original image are propagated through the network without degradation \cite{he2016}. 

Following the final residual block, the network applies a channel-wise scaling operation to yield the output representation. The overall mapping process is formally defined as:
\begin{equation}
\mathbf{F}_{center} = \text{Encoder}(\mathbf{I}_{center}) \in \mathbb{R}^{B \times 32 \times H \times W}
\end{equation}
where the spatial dimensions $H$ and $W$ remain invariant throughout the encoder via appropriate padding, maintaining the default resolution of $128 \times 128$. The resulting tensor $\mathbf{F}_{center}$ comprises $32$ feature channels. 

The output $\mathbf{F}_{center}$ acts as the geometric and textural prior for the downstream aggregation stages. It is subsequently concatenated along the channel dimension with the $32$-channel $4$D cost volume generated by the CostVolumeBuilder module. Different from previous methods that rely purely on cost volume regularization \cite{wang2023}, this joint representation explicitly feeds structural boundaries into the U-Net encoder. The structural boundaries provided by $\mathbf{F}_{center}$ enable the decoder to differentiate between true depth discontinuities and the flat cost responses induced by non-Lambertian materials, yielding physically consistent depth predictions.

\subsection{CostVolumeBuilder (代价卷积构建)}

The CostVolumeBuilder module bridges the spatial feature domain and the angular observation domain through explicit geometric projection. Conventional learning-based light field architectures implicitly process stacked angular patches using multi-dimensional convolutions, conflating photometric matching with semantic feature extraction \cite{heber2018}. This implicit coupling forces the network to generate sharp depth gradients in non-Lambertian regions where specular reflections violate the brightness consistency assumption. By constructing an explicit cost volume based on physical image warping, we decouple the angular matching from semantic feature extraction. In non-Lambertian regions, the photometric warping error remains uniformly high across all disparity hypotheses, yielding an inherently flat cost response. This flatness provides a distinct physical uncertainty signal to the network, preventing the generation of spurious depth gradients.

The module accepts the full light field tensor $\mathbf{I} \in \mathbb{R}^{B \times N \times C_{in} \times H \times W}$ and a discrete set of disparity candidates $\mathcal{D} \subset \mathbb{R}$, where $B$ is the batch size, $N=81$ is the total number of perspectives, $C_{in}$ denotes the RGB colour channels, and $H, W$ are the spatial dimensions. The central view $\mathbf{I}_c$ serves as the reference, leaving $N-1=80$ peripheral views for aggregation. For a specific disparity hypothesis $d \in \mathcal{D}$ with $|\mathcal{D}|=32$, each peripheral view $\mathbf{I}_i$ is spatially warped to align with the central view coordinate system. The warping operation $\mathcal{W}$ shifts the spatial coordinates according to the angular baseline:
\begin{equation}
\mathcal{W}(\mathbf{I}_i, d)(x,y) = \mathbf{I}_i(x + \Delta u_i d, y + \Delta v_i d)
\end{equation}
where $(x,y)$ denotes the spatial pixel coordinates, and $(\Delta u_i, \Delta v_i)$ represents the fixed angular baseline offset between the $i$-th peripheral view and the central view. The matching cost for disparity $d$ is computed by aggregating the $\ell_1$-norm photometric differences between the warped peripheral views and the central view:
\begin{equation}
\mathbf{C}(x,y,d) = \frac{1}{N-1} \sum_{i=1}^{N-1} \| \mathcal{W}(\mathbf{I}_i, d)(x,y) - \mathbf{I}_c(x,y) \|_1
\end{equation}
where $\mathbf{C}$ denotes the resulting cost volume. This operation traverses all $32$ disparity candidates, producing a $4\text{D}$ cost volume $\mathbf{C} \in \mathbb{R}^{B \times 32 \times H \times W}$. 

This explicit physical formulation contrasts with traditional Epipolar Plane Image (EPI) analysis \cite{wanner2014}, which relies on local structural linearity and is brittle under complex occlusions and specular highlights. The constructed $4\text{D}$ cost volume encodes raw geometric likelihood, while the previously extracted FeatureEncoder output $\mathbf{F}_c \in \mathbb{R}^{B \times 32 \times H \times W}$ provides high-level spatial context. The CostVolumeBuilder outputs the $4\text{D}$ tensor $\mathbf{C}$, which is concatenated with $\mathbf{F}_c$ along the channel dimension. This concatenation forms a unified representation $\mathbf{F}_{concat} \in \mathbb{R}^{B \times 64 \times H \times W}$:
\begin{equation}
\mathbf{F}_{concat} = \text{Concat}(\mathbf{F}_c, \mathbf{C})
\end{equation}
This $64$-channel tensor serves as the input to the subsequent U-Net architecture \cite{ronneberger2015}. By integrating the raw photometric cost with deep latent features, the downstream encoder can effectively process the flat uncertainty signals from non-Lambertian regions alongside fine structural textures.

\subsection{U-Net Encoder (多尺度编码器)}

The multi-scale encoder fuses the explicit physical geometry observations with semantic context cues. The 4D cost volume derived from the preceding module exhibits inherent flatness in non-Lambertian regions, functioning as a localized uncertainty signal. To accurately decode this representation and infer the surrounding structural topology, the network requires an expanded receptive field to aggregate spatial context. Conventional learning-based light field depth estimation architectures often rely on heavy multi-dimensional convolutions to directly process stacked angular patches, conflating matching errors with semantic extraction \cite{heber2018}. We decouple this by concatenating the 32-channel cost volume $\mathbf{F}_{cost} \in \mathbb{R}^{B \times N_d \times H \times W}$ with the 32-channel central view features $\mathbf{F}_{center} \in \mathbb{R}^{B \times C_{base} \times H \times W}$, where $N_d = C_{base} = 32$ denotes the number of disparity candidates and base feature channels, respectively. The formulation of this joint representation is given by:
\begin{equation}
\mathbf{F}_{concat} = \mathcal{C}(\mathbf{F}_{cost}, \mathbf{F}_{center}) \in \mathbb{R}^{B \times (N_d + C_{base}) \times H \times W}
\end{equation}
where $\mathcal{C}(\cdot)$ denotes the concatenation operation along the channel dimension, $B$ is the batch size, and $H, W$ are the spatial dimensions. The resulting 64-channel tensor preserves both photometric matching ambiguities and high-resolution texture details.

The module progressively shrinks the spatial resolution while expanding the channel dimension to extract deeper, view-invariant representations. Adopting a three-stage hierarchical downsampling mechanism inspired by U-Net architectures \cite{ronneberger2015}, the encoder trades spatial resolution for increased semantic abstraction and receptive field. Each downsampling stage employs a $3 \times 3$ convolutional layer with a stride of 2 to reduce the spatial dimensions $H$ and $W$ by half, followed by batch normalization and a parametric rectified linear unit, refined via residual learning mechanisms \cite{he2016}. The transformation at a given stage $i \in \{1, 2, 3\}$ is mathematically formalized as:
\begin{equation}
\mathbf{F}_{down}^{i} = \text{ConvBlock}_{Down} \left( \mathbf{F}_{concat}^{i-1} \right)
\end{equation}
where $\mathbf{F}_{concat}^{0} = \mathbf{F}_{concat}$ represents the initial fused input. The operator $\text{ConvBlock}_{Down}(\cdot)$ applies a strided convolution accompanied by a residual connection to prevent gradient degradation. The tensor $\mathbf{F}_{down}^{i}$ is mapped to a shape of $\mathbb{R}^{B \times C_i \times \frac{H}{2^i} \times \frac{W}{2^i}}$. Specifically, the channel dimension undergoes a sequential expansion from $C_1 = 64$ to $C_2 = 128$, and finally to $C_3 = 256$.

The downsampling hierarchy yields a multi-scale feature set that serves as the structural bridge between the geometric matching and disparity refinement stages. The deepest feature map, $\mathbf{F}_{down}^{3} \in \mathbb{R}^{B \times 256 \times \frac{H}{8} \times \frac{W}{8}}$, encodes robust global context, suppressing localized non-Lambertian photometric noise evident in the flat cost responses. While $\mathbf{F}_{down}^{3}$ is forwarded to the decoder to establish the base topological manifold, the intermediate feature maps $\mathbf{F}_{down}^{1}$ and $\mathbf{F}_{down}^{2}$ are retained. These intermediate scale outputs retain high-frequency structural boundaries necessary to resolve geometric edges. By routing these hierarchical feature representations to the subsequent skip-connection decoder module, the architecture reconciles the encoded contextual uncertainty with fine-grained spatial geometry.

\subsection{U-Net Decoder (跳跃连接解码器)}

The U-Net Decoder resolves the inherent tension between spatial granularity and contextual aggregation established during the encoding phase. In non-Lambertian light field depth estimation, localized photometric matching frequently yields flat cost volumes, signifying high epistemic uncertainty. The encoder compresses these flat signals alongside semantic features. The function of the decoder is to decompress these consolidated topological cues back into the spatial domain while restoring precise object boundaries. This architectural choice departs from standard networks that rely on multi-scale feature pyramids to independently regress depth \cite{lin2017}. We formulate the skip connections as a direct numerical alignment that enforces an evaluation of the uncertain depth cost against deterministic spatial gradients during the upsampling process.

Let $\mathbf{F}_{up_0} \in \mathbb{R}^{B \times 256 \times \frac{H}{8} \times \frac{W}{8}}$ denote the deepest feature representation generated by the U-Net Encoder, where $B$ is the batch size. Let $\mathbf{F}_{down} = \{\mathbf{F}_{down_1}, \mathbf{F}_{down_2}, \mathbf{F}_{down_3}\}$ denote the multi-scale encoder features retained during downsampling, corresponding to spatial resolutions of $\frac{H}{4} \times \frac{W}{4}$, $\frac{H}{2} \times \frac{W}{2}$, and $H \times W$, respectively. The decoder executes hierarchical feature recovery across three consecutive stages. At each stage $i \in \{1, 2, 3\}$, the previously decoded feature is upsampled and concatenated with the corresponding encoder feature. This progressive restoration mechanism is formulated as:
\begin{equation}
\mathbf{F}_{up_i} = ConvBlock_{up} \left( \mathcal{C} \left( Upsample(\mathbf{F}_{up_{i-1}}), \mathbf{F}_{down_i} \right) \right)
\end{equation}
where $\mathcal{C}(\cdot)$ denotes the concatenation operation along the channel dimension. The $Upsample(\cdot)$ operator doubles the spatial resolution using bilinear interpolation while preserving the channel dimension. The term $ConvBlock_{up}(\cdot)$ represents a parametric function consisting of two $3 \times 3$ convolutional layers, each followed by Group Normalization and a Leaky ReLU activation function. The variable $\mathbf{F}_{down_i}$ denotes the feature routed from the symmetrical encoder layer. This explicit concatenation forces the network to evaluate the uncertainty of the upsampled semantic context against the high-frequency spatial gradients preserved in $\mathbf{F}_{down_i}$.

During this synthesis, the flat cost volume regions, which initially manifest as blurred feature activations, are refined by multiplication with sharp edge cues preserved in the skip connections, effectively propagating context from adjacent Lambertian surfaces into non-Lambertian areas. Following three iterative upsampling procedures, the final decoder feature $\mathbf{F}_{up_3} \in \mathbb{R}^{B \times C_{base} \times H \times W}$ recovers the full spatial resolution. To project this latent representation into the final continuous disparity prediction, a $1 \times 1$ convolution is applied to linearly aggregate the channel-wise features:
\begin{equation}
\hat{D} = Conv_{1 \times 1} (\mathbf{F}_{up_3})
\end{equation}
where $\hat{D} \in \mathbb{R}^{B \times 1 \times H \times W}$ denotes the predicted continuous depth map, matching the spatial dimensions of the original central view input. This direct linear projection avoids a softmax operation over discrete disparity bins, allowing the network to model continuous depth variations inherent in the physical geometry \cite{eigen2014}. By relying on the skip connections to recover structural boundaries directly from the input imagery, this module mitigates the boundary bleeding artifacts that standard multi-view matching networks frequently suffer from \cite{heber2018}.

\subsection{Training Objective}

\subsection{Training Objective and Loss Function}
\label{subsec:loss_function}

The training objective jointly optimizes geometric depth regression and physical material decomposition. The unified dual-mask model and the material component-aware fusion architecture necessitate a composite loss function that enforces both data fidelity to the ground truth depth and strict adherence to the physical constraints of light-matter interaction. The overall objective function is defined as:
\begin{equation}
\label{eq:total_loss}
\mathcal{L}_{total} = \lambda_{d} \mathcal{L}_{depth} + \lambda_{m} \mathcal{L}_{mat} + \lambda_{p} \mathcal{L}_{phys},
\end{equation}
where $\mathcal{L}_{depth}$, $\mathcal{L}_{mat}$, and $\mathcal{L}_{phys}$ denote the depth estimation, material classification, and physical regularization terms, respectively. The scalar weights $\lambda_{d}$, $\lambda_{m}$, and $\lambda_{p}$ balance the contributions of these heterogeneous objectives.

\subsubsection{Depth Estimation Loss}
Accurate disparity prediction in non-Lambertian regions requires decoupling the geometric signal from view-dependent reflections. The depth loss operates on the material-component-aware fused depth map, formulated as $D_{fused} = w_d D_{EPI} + w_s D_{specular} + w_{sc} D_{scatter}$. To mitigate the adverse effects of high-frequency noise in specular regions and ensure robust convergence, we employ a Scale-Invariant Logarithmic error (SILog) combined with an edge-aware smoothness regularization \cite{godard2019}:
\begin{equation}
\label{eq:depth_loss}
\mathcal{L}_{depth} = \frac{1}{HW} \sum_{x,y} \left\| \log \left( D_{fused}(x,y) + \epsilon \right) - \log \left( D_{GT}(x,y) + \epsilon \right) \right\|_1 + \lambda_{s} \mathcal{L}_{smooth}.
\end{equation}
The logarithmic transformation directly penalizes the relative Mean Absolute Error (MAE), allocating proportional gradients to both nearby Lambertian surfaces and distant non-Lambertian structures. The edge-aware smoothness term $\mathcal{L}_{smooth} = \sum_{x,y} \left( \partial_x D_{fused} e^{-\|\partial_x I\|} + \partial_y D_{fused} e^{-{\|\partial_y I\|}} \right)^2$ suppresses gradients in $D_{fused}$ where the reference image $I$ lacks strong spatial edges, effectively regularizing depth discontinuities without over-smoothing physical object boundaries \cite{eigen2014}.

\subsubsection{Material Classification Loss}
To establish a reliable foundation for the material component-aware fusion strategy, the network must accurately distinguish between diffuse, specular, and scattering domains based on the angular 2D-DFT spectrum. We implement a standard Cross-Entropy loss across the discrete material classes:
\begin{equation}
\label{eq:mat_loss}
\mathcal{L}_{mat} = - \frac{1}{HW} \sum_{x,y} \sum_{c \in \{d, s, sc\}} Y_{c}(x,y) \log \left( P_{c}(x,y) \right),
\end{equation}
where $P_{c}$ is the predicted probability of material class $c$ derived from the lightweight $O(HW)$ angular spectrum analysis, and $Y_{c}$ is the corresponding pseudo-label generated by geometric consistency descriptors (GCD) and thresholded pixel roughness. Minimizing $\mathcal{L}_{mat}$ sharpens the spectral feature representation, effectively driving the model toward the targeted classification accuracy while isolating the view-dependent high-frequency components inherent in specular and scattering wavefronts.

\subsubsection{Physical Consistency Constraints}
The physical regularization term enforces Maxwell-equation-derived wavevector constraints on the predicted BRDF weights and the dual-mask model. Conventional unconstrained neural networks suffer from output saturation or physically implausible reflectance combinations. To resolve this, we enforce a strict energy conservation law on the material weights and regulate the variation of the angular direction mask $M_{ang}(x,y)$:
\begin{equation}
\label{eq:phys_loss}
\mathcal{L}_{phys} = \frac{1}{HW} \sum_{x,y} \Bigg[ \underbrace{\left( w_d(x,y) + w_s(x,y) + w_{sc}(x,y) - 1 \right)^2}_{\text{Energy Conservation}} + \underbrace{\gamma \left\| \nabla M_{ang}(x,y) \right\|_2^2}_{\text{Wavevector Smoothness}} \Bigg].
\end{equation}
The first term enforces that the predicted diffuse ($w_d$), specular ($w_s$), and scattering ($w_{sc}$) weights sum to unity, consistent with fundamental physical BRDF models \cite{blinn1977}. The second term penalizes rapid spatial fluctuations in the deflection vector field $M_{ang}$. This total variation penalty assumes that surface normals vary smoothly across contiguous material surfaces, a prerequisite for valid light field propagation \cite{zhang2023}. 

The balancing weights are empirically set as $\lambda_{d} = 1.0$, $\lambda_{m} = 0.1$, and $\lambda_{p} = 0.01$. The depth regression term dominates the optimization landscape, while the classification and physical regularization terms act as guiding priors. Optimization is performed using the AdamW algorithm ($\beta_1=0.9, \beta_2=0.999$). To accommodate the $9 \times 9$ light field volume within the 24GB RTX 3090 memory constraint, training utilizes Automatic Mixed Precision (AMP) and a base batch size of 1, with gradients accumulated over 4 steps. The learning rate is scheduled using CosineAnnealingLR \cite{heber2018}, decaying from an initial $1 \times 10^{-4}$ to $1 \times 10^{-6}$, ensuring stable convergence across the varying loss magnitudes. With this optimized training configuration established, we now evaluate the proposed Unified Dual-Mask Physical Model across a diverse collection of Light Field datasets.

