\section{Conclusion}

This paper addresses the severe degradation in light field depth estimation caused by violations of the viewpoint consistency assumption. To mitigate the depth blurring and texture copying artifacts prevalent in non-Lambertian scenes, we propose a Unified Dual-Mask Physical Model. By parsing pixel-wise physical reflection properties from angular observations, the proposed framework replaces fragile data-driven dependencies with explicit physical priors, enabling robust geometric reconstruction in complex optical environments. The principal contributions of this work are summarized as follows:

\begin{itemize}
    \item We develop a dual-mask physical model based on MRI-like angular frequency analysis. This mechanism inversely resolves pixel-level physical reflection types from angular samples, breaking the reliance on purely data-driven heuristics. Operating with low computational complexity, the model provides a robust physical prior that directly resolves the viewpoint consistency failure responsible for texture copying in specular and scattering regions.
    \item We design a material-component-aware depth fusion architecture incorporating a Multi-scale Angular Cost Volume (MACVO-Net). This architecture resolves the view undersampling and directional rigidity of implicit EPI frameworks under complex reflections. By fusing physical material priors with cost volume uncertainty signals, the network dynamically adapts its matching strategy: relying on geometric correspondence in Lambertian domains while suppressing erroneous textures via multi-scale context propagation in non-Lambertian domains.
    \item We introduce a Geometric Consistency Descriptor (GCD) utilizing a double subtraction strategy to amplify the energy contrast across distinct reflection types. Empirical evaluations demonstrate that while baseline models catastrophically fail in pure Lambertian and non-Lambertian domains, the proposed physical integration substantially stabilizes depth estimation. The feature engineering yields significant energy contrast improvements, validating the efficacy of the physical model in breaking the accuracy bottleneck in highly reflective scenarios.
\end{itemize}

Integrating physical reflection modeling with geometric deep learning establishes a robust paradigm for non-Lambertian 3D vision. Future efforts will focus on optimizing the angular frequency extraction pipeline to facilitate real-time deployment in autonomous navigation and computational photography systems.
